	<entry>
		<title>By: mj</title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="/index.php/datamgmt/datadesign/beginning-stages-of-a-dr-plan-for-sql-se/#comment-2164" type="text/html" />

		<author>
			<name>mj</name>
			
		</author>

		<id>/index.php/2009/11/beginning-stages-of-a-dr-plan-for-sql-se/#comment-2164</id>
		<updated>2009-11-18T22:41:45Z</updated>
		<published>2009-11-18T22:41:45Z</published>
		<content type="html" xml:base="/index.php/datamgmt/datadesign/beginning-stages-of-a-dr-plan-for-sql-se/#comment-2164"><![CDATA[<p>When I was asked to setup write a DR plan I reviewed the Microsoft Best Practices and wrote it up.</p>
<p>I was unprepared when the system administrators informed me that they were not interested in mirroring and instead were going to utilize SAN replication and snapshots to replicate data. </p>
<p>The DR site would be available by using an alias which will point to the source site (ServerName, ip_address1, subnet_1) and (ServerName, ip_address1, subnet_2).</p>
<p>The was the first I had ever heard of this solution.  Has anyone else had any experience like this?</p>
]]></content>
